                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18390204-810-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390204-810-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390204-810-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18390204-cd-240" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390204-810-offence-1 t18390204-cd-240"></join>5th of feb<lb></lb>ruary</rs>, 1 metal cap, value 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of the <persName id="t18390204-name-1461" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1461" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390204-810-offence-1 t18390204-name-1461"></join>London Dock Company</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1462" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1462" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1462" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1462" type="given" value="HUGH"></interp>HUGH SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant-foreman at the London Docks. On the 5th of February I was going towards the North-quay, and saw the prisoner, who was a stranger—I made some inquiries of him, and he walked away—I followed him, and asked what he wanted—he said, "Nothing"—he had a blue coat on, over a smock frock—I asked what he had got under his coat—he said, "Nothing"—I put my hand under it, and found this piece of brass—I saw a belt under his frock, his frock was turned in, and that supported the piece of metal—I asked where he got it—he said he picked it up, and pointed to a place where it came from—he then began to cry, and begged my pardon.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1463" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1463" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1463" type="surname" value="RUDKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1463" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>DANIEL RUDKINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a constable of the London Docks. On the 5th of February I took the prisoner from the witness, with this metal cap—the prisoner said he picked it up—I went to examine the jiggers and crabs, and I found a deficiency, and this piece fitted exactly—the nuts and staples were left in the crab, and this had been taken away—he was not in the employ of the Docks, and had no right there.</p>
